#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:154
msgid "Accessing the data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:156
msgid "The underlying data of a masked array can be accessed in several ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:158
msgid ""
"through the :attr:`~MaskedArray.data` attribute. The output is a view of the "
"array as a :class:`numpy.ndarray` or one of its subclasses, depending on the "
"type of the underlying data at the masked array creation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:162
msgid ""
"through the :meth:`~MaskedArray.__array__` method. The output is then a :"
"class:`numpy.ndarray`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:165
msgid ""
"by directly taking a view of the masked array as a :class:`numpy.ndarray` or "
"one of its subclass (which is actually what using the :attr:`~MaskedArray."
"data` attribute does)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:169
msgid "by using the :func:`getdata` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:172
msgid ""
"None of these methods is completely satisfactory if some entries have been "
"marked as invalid. As a general rule, where a representation of the array is "
"required without any masked entries, it is recommended to fill the array "
"with the :meth:`filled` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:180
msgid "Accessing the mask"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:182
msgid ""
"The mask of a masked array is accessible through its :attr:`~MaskedArray."
"mask` attribute. We must keep in mind that a ``True`` entry in the mask "
"indicates an *invalid* data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:186
msgid ""
"Another possibility is to use the :func:`getmask` and :func:`getmaskarray` "
"functions. ``getmask(x)`` outputs the mask of ``x`` if ``x`` is a masked "
"array, and the special value :data:`nomask` otherwise. ``getmaskarray(x)`` "
"outputs the mask of ``x`` if ``x`` is a masked array. If ``x`` has no "
"invalid entry or is not a masked array, the function outputs  a boolean "
"array of ``False`` with as many elements as ``x``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:197
msgid "Accessing only the valid entries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:199
msgid ""
"To retrieve only the valid entries, we can use the inverse of the mask as an "
"index. The inverse of the mask can be calculated with the :func:`numpy."
"logical_not` function or simply with the ``~`` operator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:212
msgid ""
"Another way to retrieve the valid data is to use the :meth:`compressed` "
"method, which returns a one-dimensional :class:`~numpy.ndarray` (or one of "
"its subclasses, depending on the value of the :attr:`~MaskedArray.baseclass` "
"attribute):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/maskedarray.generic.rst:220
msgid "Note that the output of :meth:`compressed` is always 1D."
msgstr ""

